[1]
Date: Thu 13 Nov 2003
From: Cheryle Becker <Cheryl-b@phd5.state.id.us>

Alligator Farming in Idaho
--------------------------
In response to the recent posting by Steve Grenard, I would like to clarify
the information about alligators in Idaho. The farm in question has raised
alligators for the meat and hide trade for many years. This is possible
due to the artesian wells on the property. The water from the wells is over
90 degrees F. These alligators are raised in enclosed locked barns.
The owner of the farm has been very responsible and has been in touch with
some well-known researchers in Louisiana and Florida during this
incident. He initiated the testing that led to a diagnosis and agreed to
destroy the remaining 600 alligators. He has completed disinfection of the
barn.
Investigators from South Central District Health have been on site at the
farm and provided the testing and interview of the workers. The worker with
a positive West Nile antibody test had completed necropsies of alligators
during the early period when the cause of the alligator die-off was not
known. This worker had minimal symptoms that were not recognized at the
time. Idaho health districts trapped mosquitoes during the summer season
with no mosquitoes found to be positive for West Nile virus. Trapping was
completed within 10 miles of the farm. We will continue to trap mosquitoes
in the area of the farm next spring.
This incident should prompt us to look for unusual situations that provide
an avenue for the introduction of emerging infectious diseases.
--
Cheryle Becker, RN
Manager, Communicable Disease Division
South Central District Health
Twin Falls, Idaho
<cheryl-b@phd5.state.id.us>
