Date: Thu 13 Nov 2003
From: Leslie Tengelsen <tengelse@idhw.state.id.us>

Re: Alligator Farming in Idaho And West Nile Virus
--------------------------------------------------
Alligator farming does occur in Idaho with the aid of geothermal waters and
enclosed structures. It has gone on for many years. These animals are not
part of the pet trade. These animals are raised for hides and meat just
like those produced in more temperate states.
Cloacal swabs and tissue swabs yielded positive real-time RT-PCR results
from these imported hatchlings confirming West Nile virus (WNV) in this
group. The individual who had seroconverted did have an extraordinary
exposure while carrying out a necropsy in the absence of personal
protection, strongly suggesting a direct blood-borne exposure. None of the
handlers that dealt with daily operations seroconverted.
We have been doing extensive surveillance for WNV in Idaho (mosquito,
avian, equine, and human) for 2 years now, and with the exception of
several imported human and equine cases, have not found any evidence of WNV
within our borders. We attempted to collect mosquitoes around the alligator
farm; however, temperatures had dropped and no mosquitoes were found in the
collection traps.
There is much to be learned from WNV-infected alligators. I believe that
studies are ongoing in other states to more clearly elucidate the biology
of this virus in these animals. Perhaps then scientists will more clearly
understand the risks associated with animals that might make it into the
pet trade.
It is important to realize that these animals do apparently shed virus
fecally, as was proven by our positive cloacal swabs. They also clearly
have virus in their tissues, so it would be prudent to handle them
accordingly and presume that a risk is present.
--
Leslie Tengelsen, PhD, DVM
Deputy State Epidemiologist
450 W. State St., 4th Floor
Boise, ID 83720
<tengelse@idhw.state.id.us>
